<font color="#FF0000">I GREAT YOU FROM A PALE HORSE</font><br>
<tt>Fri Aug 29 21:12:25 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I rode my pale horse through the paddies,<br>
watching the water turn from brown to red,<br>
and the stink from bad to worse...<br><br>
who am I? surly you know?<br><br>
I stood by when the fire fights flew,<br>
the napalm crackled, the smell of<br>
burning flesh mixed with clothing,<br>
trees, and other materials - so sweet.<br><br>
I was in the tunnels, dimmly lighted by<br>
smoking dead candles, waiting for you G.I.<br>
rats, light in one hand, gun in the other,<br>
trying to see me before I saw you. Some times<br>
you won, sometimes you didn't. I left you my<br>
dead and dying so your cameraman would be happy.<br><br>
Who am I? I was your lover in the night, wasn't I?<br><br>
And in the villages, smiling at you by day,<br>
at the wire by night, nailing you.<br>
smiling, always smiling, yus sir, yus sir.<br>
Take the mama san, take my daughter, take my son,<br>
may your manhood fall off in pus and disease,<br>
but in my sights, no more yus sir, just dead, sir.<br><br>
I was there to here you them Slopes,<br>
gooks, horrible names, non human names,<br>
and I heard them call you back names,<br>
animal off spring, capitalistic slurs, both<br>
of you couldn't see me, though I rode my horse<br>
over your thick heads...<br><br>
You must know me by now, you did so much for me.<br><br>
I saw all the bullshit of both sides at the same time,<br>
cowards and murderers knew no loyalty.<br>
Black pants sadistic killers met green clad murders,<br>
time and time again. Your side put medicine into<br>
the arms of the children, and the other side had<br>
to chop off those arms. Ah, children of the beast,<br>
children of the war, children who had no childhood,<br>
and only had horror for a mother, and tragedy for<br>
a father... <br><br>
I whispered in the ear of LBJ and Henry Killenger,<br>
just as I did to Diem, and to Uncle Ho.<br>
I showed them how to raise the stakes, to spread<br>
the rumors in the villages, by word of mouth and<br>
deed, and in cities, by media and television.<br><br>
You all were such fools, that my larder will be full<br>
for years to come. Do you know my name yet?<br><br>
Do not glory in my name ever. Do not be proud that you<br>
looked on my handywork. Be shamed forever that you <br>
played at my card table, that you broke bread with me,<br>
never be proud, be you round eye or slant eye, because<br>
I am the great equilizer, and your time may still be<br>
coming.  I will come for you all, those that I missed<br>
years ago, I will find later on.  <br><br>
Do you recognize my smell now.<br><br>
I am your death. . .<br>

